language Essence 1.3

$ Social Golfers Problem — Formulation 9: 3D Boolean Matrix
$
$ Domain:  matrix indexed by [int(1..w), int(1..g), int(1..nGolfers)] of bool
$
$ Information carried by the domain:
$   - Minimal: each entry records whether golfer p is in group j during week i
$   - No structural guarantees beyond the boolean assignment
$
$ Information NOT carried (must be constrained explicitly):
$   - Each golfer is in exactly one group per week (assignment)
$   - Each group has exactly s golfers (group size)
$
$ Explicit constraints needed:
$   1. Assignment constraint: each golfer in exactly one group per week
$   2. Group size constraint: each group has exactly s golfers per week
$   3. Pairing constraint: no pair of golfers shares a group more than once
$
$ Compared to Formulation 8 (integer matrix):
$   - The integer group-assignment is "channelled" into a 3D boolean matrix.
$   - This is the classic 0/1 matrix encoding. Every structural property
$     must be stated explicitly, making this one of the most verbose formulations.
$   - However, this encoding can be advantageous for solvers that exploit
$     boolean structure or arc consistency on binary variables.

given w, g, s : int(1..)

letting nGolfers be g * s

find sched : matrix indexed by [int(1..w), int(1..g), int(1..nGolfers)] of bool

$ Assignment constraint: each golfer is in exactly one group per week
such that
    forAll i : int(1..w) .
        forAll p : int(1..nGolfers) .
            (sum j : int(1..g) . toInt(sched[i, j, p])) = 1,

$ Group size constraint: each group has exactly s golfers per week
such that
    forAll i : int(1..w) .
        forAll j : int(1..g) .
            (sum p : int(1..nGolfers) . toInt(sched[i, j, p])) = s,

$ Pairing constraint: no two golfers share a group more than once
such that
    forAll p1 : int(1..nGolfers) .
        forAll p2 : int(1..nGolfers) .
            p1 < p2 ->
            (sum i : int(1..w) .
                sum j : int(1..g) .
                    toInt(sched[i, j, p1] /\ sched[i, j, p2])
            ) <= 1
